or what people might be willing to divulge,

267
00:11:38,220 --> 00:11:40,940
and we're limited by what it's legal to ask.

268
00:11:40,940 --> 00:11:43,500
We need to decide what labels and groups to include.

269
00:11:43,500 --> 00:11:46,260
Like for gender questions, what will our options be?

270
00:11:46,260 --> 00:11:48,220
I know that there are non-binary humans

271
00:11:48,220 --> 00:11:50,780
for whom the labels like male and female,

272
00:11:50,780 --> 00:11:53,700
or like man and woman, don't really apply.

273
00:11:53,700 --> 00:11:56,260
So how do you take into account that

274
00:11:56,260 --> 00:11:59,620
when the government requires that you ask like,

275
00:11:59,620 --> 00:12:00,740
male, female?

276
00:12:01,740 --> 00:12:04,180
Also, making a survey is an art unto itself,

277
00:12:04,180 --> 00:12:05,660
and it's possible to ask questions

278
00:12:05,660 --> 00:12:08,940
and elicit a response that you did not intend.

279
00:12:09,940 --> 00:12:13,980
Just so you all know, federal contractors are required

280
00:12:13,980 --> 00:12:16,700
to request this information

281
00:12:16,700 --> 00:12:19,900
for the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.

282
00:12:19,900 --> 00:12:23,460
There's certain questions that you have to ask,

283
00:12:23,460 --> 00:12:26,780
and if they don't match up with what you'd like to ask,

284
00:12:26,780 --> 00:12:28,540
that leads to having like multiple surveys,

285
00:12:28,980 --> 00:12:30,740
which causes survey fatigue.

286
00:12:30,740 --> 00:12:32,180
There's also suspicion.

287
00:12:32,180 --> 00:12:34,780
So find out what you need to do

288
00:12:34,780 --> 00:12:38,340
and decide what the best balance is for you.

289
00:12:38,340 --> 00:12:42,580
Great balance in terms of like survey fatigue

290
00:12:42,580 --> 00:12:45,180
or like getting the questions answered that you really want.

291
00:12:46,900 --> 00:12:49,700
So now we get to the part that I find really interesting.

292
00:12:49,700 --> 00:12:52,700
What actually constitutes sufficient diversity?

293
00:12:54,100 --> 00:12:57,500
Well, it turns out with zero diverse candidates in a pool,

294
00:12:57,540 --> 00:12:59,180
you're obviously not gonna hire anyone

295
00:12:59,180 --> 00:13:01,220
from an underrepresented group.

296
00:13:01,220 --> 00:13:02,620
But according to a handful of studies

297
00:13:02,620 --> 00:13:04,420
that the Harvard Business Review did,

298
00:13:04,420 --> 00:13:07,420
even with one candidate from a minority group in the pool,

299
00:13:08,620 --> 00:13:11,420
that person has like zero chance of actually getting hired

300
00:13:11,420 --> 00:13:13,980
because of our preference for the status quo.

301
00:13:13,980 --> 00:13:17,380
And there's this great quote in that article.

302
00:13:18,900 --> 00:13:22,380
Deviating from the norm can be risky for decision makers

303
00:13:22,380 --> 00:13:24,260
because people tend to ostracize people

304
00:13:24,260 --> 00:13:25,660
who are different from the group.

305
00:13:25,660 --> 00:13:27,060
So for women and minorities,

306
00:13:27,620 --> 00:13:29,180
having your differences made salient

307
00:13:29,180 --> 00:13:31,940
can lead to an inference of incompetence.

308
00:13:31,940 --> 00:13:34,820
So if you're the only woman in a pool of finalists,

309
00:13:34,820 --> 00:13:37,500
it highlights how she is different from the norm

310
00:13:37,500 --> 00:13:41,100
and makes her inherently riskier candidate

311
00:13:41,100 --> 00:13:43,060
and likely one that you won't go with.

312
00:13:45,380 --> 00:13:47,420
But if you have even two people

313
00:13:47,420 --> 00:13:48,860
from an underrepresented group,

314
00:13:48,860 --> 00:13:51,100
they actually stand a chance of getting hired.

315
00:13:52,100 --> 00:13:56,140
The odds of hiring a minority were 193 times greater

316
00:13:56,140 --> 00:13:57,780
if there were at least two minority candidates

317
00:13:57,780 --> 00:13:59,220
in the finalist pool,

318
00:13:59,220 --> 00:14:01,300
controlling for the number of other minority

319
00:14:01,300 --> 00:14:03,940
and white finalists controlling for pool size.

320
00:14:03,940 --> 00:14:05,540
So like that is not inflated.

321
00:14:06,420 --> 00:14:07,620
How impressive is that?

322
00:14:12,060 --> 00:14:15,540
But two candidates, come on, that's a pretty low bar.

323
00:14:15,540 --> 00:14:16,660
What we saw was if there was like

324
00:14:16,660 --> 00:14:18,460
a relatively small pool of finalists,

325
00:14:18,460 --> 00:14:20,700
like six finalists, eight finalists,

326
00:14:20,700 --> 00:14:22,020
if you've got an applicant pool

327
00:14:22,020 --> 00:14:24,540
for a role like software engineer,

328
00:14:24,540 --> 00:14:25,860
you're gonna have far more candidates

329
00:14:25,860 --> 00:14:26,700
to choose from.

330
00:14:26,700 --> 00:14:27,820
So even if you have two people

331
00:14:27,820 --> 00:14:30,300
from a minority group represented,

332
00:14:30,300 --> 00:14:32,500
if there's a thousand people in the in group,

333
00:14:32,500 --> 00:14:35,180
even if you put aside unconscious bias,

334
00:14:35,180 --> 00:14:37,220
which totally exists and will whittle down

335
00:14:37,220 --> 00:14:39,660
your diversity of your candidate pool

336
00:14:39,660 --> 00:14:41,660
every step of the pipeline,

337
00:14:41,660 --> 00:14:43,980
and if you put aside our status quo fix

338
00:14:43,980 --> 00:14:45,300
of having two candidates,

339
00:14:45,300 --> 00:14:47,780
you're still statistically unlikely to hire someone

340
00:14:47,780 --> 00:14:49,780
different from the status quo

341
00:14:49,780 --> 00:14:52,540
because you have two of them against a thousand other

342
00:14:52,540 --> 00:14:54,620
probably equally qualified candidates.

343
00:14:55,620 --> 00:14:57,940
So what can we do then?

344
00:14:58,900 --> 00:15:00,580
I've got a crazy idea.

345
00:15:00,580 --> 00:15:02,340
Why not go for parity with the eligible

346
00:15:02,340 --> 00:15:05,340
labor force in the US?

347
00:15:05,340 --> 00:15:07,940
Then at least if the top of your funnel is balanced,

348
00:15:07,940 --> 00:15:09,660
you stand a greater chance of having those people

349
00:15:09,660 --> 00:15:11,540
make it through your hiring process.

350
00:15:12,500 --> 00:15:14,220
Not that it's smooth sailing from there,

351
00:15:14,220 --> 00:15:16,100
we still need to institute systems

352
00:15:16,100 --> 00:15:17,940
to limit the effective unconscious bias

353
00:15:17,940 --> 00:15:19,620
in the rest of the hiring pipeline,

354
00:15:19,620 --> 00:15:21,780
but at least it's a start.

355
00:15:21,780 --> 00:15:23,860
This is part of a table of race and gender

356
00:15:23,980 --> 00:15:25,540
in the potential labor force.

357
00:15:25,540 --> 00:15:27,780
The base number is a thousand.

358
00:15:27,780 --> 00:15:30,700
So for 2017, the total number of black women

359
00:15:30,700 --> 00:15:33,540
in the workforce was 10.5 million

360
00:15:33,540 --> 00:15:35,620
out of 17.5 million black women

361
00:15:35,620 --> 00:15:38,220
who could have been in the labor force.

362
00:15:38,220 --> 00:15:40,660
Not all of these people are qualified for every job

363
00:15:40,660 --> 00:15:42,140
or even are interested,

364
00:15:42,140 --> 00:15:44,660
but if we support programs that give training

365
00:15:44,660 --> 00:15:47,100
and opportunities to underrepresented groups,

366
00:15:47,100 --> 00:15:49,260
while we also try to get as close as possible

367
00:15:49,260 --> 00:15:51,900
to having our pipeline represent the population pool,

368
00:15:51,900 --> 00:15:55,020
someday those might converge and we'll get there.

369
00:15:55,020 --> 00:15:57,300
But like, you know, aim for the stars.

370
00:15:59,180 --> 00:16:01,100
We're doing this now at Clover Health.

371
00:16:02,260 --> 00:16:04,660
So that glorious future that I talked about,

372
00:16:04,660 --> 00:16:05,820
what does it look like?

373
00:16:07,380 --> 00:16:09,580
I found out after I did my MVP

374
00:16:09,580 --> 00:16:11,660
and when I was like halfway through V2

375
00:16:11,660 --> 00:16:12,860
that there's actually a company

376
00:16:12,860 --> 00:16:14,700
that does a lot of this for you,

377
00:16:14,700 --> 00:16:17,060
and we ultimately decided to use them for the future

378
00:16:17,060 --> 00:16:20,260
so that engineering hours don't need to support this web app,

379
00:16:20,260 --> 00:16:23,620
this like hacky web app that I made indefinitely.

380
00:16:23,620 --> 00:16:27,500
We didn't discover until we were like deep in V2.

381
00:16:27,500 --> 00:16:29,540
So like, could we have done research to discover

382
00:16:29,540 --> 00:16:32,780
that this company existed first and save ourselves some work?

383
00:16:32,780 --> 00:16:34,140
Absolutely.

384
00:16:34,140 --> 00:16:35,820
Would anyone have thought to Google it

385
00:16:35,820 --> 00:16:37,700
before I made my MVP?

386
00:16:37,700 --> 00:16:38,980
Probably not.

387
00:16:38,980 --> 00:16:40,140
We found out about this company

388
00:16:40,140 --> 00:16:42,380
through our diversity and inclusion manager

389
00:16:42,380 --> 00:16:44,820
who joined right after I made my MVP.

390
00:16:44,820 --> 00:16:48,100
So if you have diversity and inclusion folks at your company,

391
00:16:48,100 --> 00:16:49,540
talk to them early.

392
00:16:50,500 --> 00:16:52,300
This company is called Atypica,

393
00:16:52,300 --> 00:16:57,300
and they'll, if you connect them with your recruit track,

394
00:16:57,780 --> 00:16:59,820
or recruiting tracking software,

395
00:16:59,820 --> 00:17:02,260
and give them like an API key or something like that,

396
00:17:02,260 --> 00:17:05,100
they will look at your candidate pool

397
00:17:05,100 --> 00:17:08,660
and do the slicing by role or by department,

398
00:17:08,660 --> 00:17:10,980
by stage in the pipeline,

399
00:17:10,980 --> 00:17:15,980
and they also do analysis to figure out

400
00:17:16,460 --> 00:17:19,100
how to solve the sparsity problem of the data

401
00:17:19,100 --> 00:17:21,900
so that they have like an 80 or 90 something percent

402
00:17:21,900 --> 00:17:25,340
accuracy rate in determining gender and race,

403
00:17:25,340 --> 00:17:27,500
and they don't do it just by like photo recognition

404
00:17:27,500 --> 00:17:29,140
or like facial recognition,

405
00:17:29,140 --> 00:17:31,340
so I think that's pretty cool.

406
00:17:33,980 --> 00:17:35,580
If you don't have the budget to outsource

407
00:17:35,580 --> 00:17:36,820
the way that we ultimately did,

408
00:17:36,820 --> 00:17:39,780
the web app we talked about is perfectly usable though.

409
00:17:39,780 --> 00:17:42,460
It probably requires a little further iteration

410
00:17:42,460 --> 00:17:44,100
to handle the sparsity of data problem

411
00:17:44,100 --> 00:17:45,940
that we were talking about,

412
00:17:45,940 --> 00:17:47,940
but even if your time is limited,

413
00:17:47,940 --> 00:17:50,340
the MVP is still better than nothing at all.

414
00:17:51,340 --> 00:17:52,380
If you go this route,

415
00:17:52,380 --> 00:17:55,060
make sure to include any DNI people at your company.

416
00:17:55,060 --> 00:17:57,260
You'll need weigh in from HR and recruiting

417
00:17:57,260 --> 00:17:59,180
as well as possibly legal,

418
00:17:59,180 --> 00:18:01,060
but if you're willing to do the work,

419
00:18:01,060 --> 00:18:03,340
most of the time folks are happy to give you their opinion

420
00:18:03,340 --> 00:18:05,340
and send you on their way,

421
00:18:05,340 --> 00:18:07,140
but don't try to do this without the knowledge

422
00:18:07,140 --> 00:18:11,620
of what's legal without like consulting anyone.

423
00:18:11,620 --> 00:18:14,260
Doing the problem solving without these people

424
00:18:14,260 --> 00:18:16,620
would have been a huge mistake for me,

425
00:18:16,620 --> 00:18:18,620
because I'm just an engineer

426
00:18:18,620 --> 00:18:21,940
and you can't just tell me to implement a data ingest

427
00:18:21,940 --> 00:18:23,940
because I'll do that,

428
00:18:23,940 --> 00:18:27,580
but I should be part of the design of the thing,

429
00:18:27,580 --> 00:18:29,580
but I don't have all the answers about like

430
00:18:29,580 --> 00:18:32,460
what we should do, what we can do legally.

431
00:18:33,900 --> 00:18:35,380
And also you can't just like

432
00:18:36,660 --> 00:18:39,100
not include engineering in this task,

433
00:18:39,100 --> 00:18:42,540
because obviously we all know that we have useful opinions,

434
00:18:42,540 --> 00:18:44,900
and boy do we have opinions.

435
00:18:46,780 --> 00:18:49,180
So the next challenge is how do you integrate data

436
00:18:49,180 --> 00:18:51,900
for current employees with information

437
00:18:51,900 --> 00:18:54,980
that's available for your hiring pipeline?

438
00:18:55,900 --> 00:18:57,780
They're like two separate sources of information

439
00:18:57,780 --> 00:19:01,860
and geez, but like reconciling them is like pulling teeth.

440
00:19:03,100 --> 00:19:04,860
I just found out earlier this week though,

441
00:19:04,860 --> 00:19:07,580
that Etipica now has like an API

442
00:19:07,580 --> 00:19:11,340
that you can use for looking at information,

443
00:19:11,340 --> 00:19:14,580
I think about like promotion and retention and stuff

444
00:19:14,580 --> 00:19:15,660
for your existing employees.

445
00:19:15,660 --> 00:19:17,980
So hey, maybe this problem is basically solved for me

446
00:19:17,980 --> 00:19:20,700
and I just need to go check out their API documentation,

447
00:19:20,700 --> 00:19:23,300
which I'm honestly likely gonna do on the plane home.

448
00:19:25,500 --> 00:19:28,980
So now when you identify departments or roles

449
00:19:28,980 --> 00:19:32,260
where there isn't representation across different groups,

450
00:19:32,260 --> 00:19:33,540
the next step is going back

451
00:19:33,540 --> 00:19:35,220
and sourcing from those missing groups.

452
00:19:35,220 --> 00:19:38,220
If there's a big drop off at one step of the recruiting funnel,

453
00:19:38,220 --> 00:19:40,820
investigate why people are leaving there.

